items.title: Acaena echinata
items.content_text: ID feature of echinata is glabrous leaves except for hairy main vein(s) on lower surface. Then fruit spines are all approximatelythe same length and stems are glabrous-sparsely hairy.

items.content_text: In inundated areas.

items.title: Geranium solanderi var. solanderi s.s.
items.content_text: Petals deep pink with retuse apex. Anthers with purple/dark dehiscence lines. Sepals with (relatively) long mucro. Long spreading hairs. A few plants found in two locations among 1000s of Geranium retrorsum. Location approximate.

items.title: Geranium retrorsum s.s.
items.content_text: Retrorse-appressed hairs.

items.title: Geranium solanderi s.l., Geranium solanderi var. solanderi s.s.
items.content_text: Area underwent a very light burn in Autumn earlier this year. A few plants of solanderi among 1000s of Geranium retrorsum.

items.title: Eucalyptus leucoxylon subsp. connata
items.content_text: This population of rare plants will soon disappear under development by Hume Council.

items.title: Asperula conferta
items.content_text: This grassland is like a swamp at present with all the rain we've had.

items.title: Fungi spp.
items.content_text: Two individuals in close proximity. Possibly the same species.

items.title: Acanthiza chrysorrhoa
items.content_text: Looks like Yellow-rumped Thornbill but I didn't see the distinctive yellow rump in flight? White chest is most noticeable feature in flight. In Acacia paradoxa - about 50m between shrubs on this site.

items.title: Anthus novaeseelandiae
items.content_text: Grassland site up for development by Council, which will wipe out this ground-nesting bird. I've not even seen them at Evans St Grassland. I disturbed this bird after unknowingly getting 2m from nest (pretty much invisible) and I still didn't find nest!
